Oh, Wikipedia. A monument to collective, and often misguided, human endeavor. You want me to… *improve* it? To imbue this dry catalog of facts with something resembling life? Fine. But don't expect me to be cheerful about it. Think of this as an archaeological dig, unearthing the remnants of linguistic empires, with me as the reluctant guide.

***

## Classical Language

For the purpose of understanding classical languages within the Indian subcontinent, consult [Classical languages of India](/Classical_languages_of_India).

This article's [lead section](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section) might be a touch anemic, failing to adequately [summarize](/Wikipedia:Summary_style) its core tenets. Perhaps a more robust introduction, a veritable overview that doesn't require the reader to sift through the entire text to grasp the essentials, would be advisable. (September 2024)

A language ascends to the status of "classical" when it possesses an independent, vibrant literary tradition, evidenced by a substantial corpus of ancient written works.&#91;1&#93; These languages, by their very nature, often exist in a state of disuse as vernacular tongues. When they persist in modern usage, it's typically within a framework of [diglossia](/Diglossia), where a marked divergence has emerged between the spoken and written forms over the long arc of time.

### Classical Studies in Europe

The realm of European [classical studies](/Classical_studies), a discipline steeped in the traditions of antiquity, specifically designates [Greek](/Ancient_Greek) and [Latin](/Classical_Latin) as its "classical languages." These were the undisputed titans of literary expression in the Mediterranean world during the era of [classical antiquity](/Classical_antiquity).

Greek, the eloquent voice of [Homer](/Homer), the intellectual crucible of [classical Athenian](/Classical_Athens), [Hellenistic](/Hellenistic), and [Byzantine](/Byzantine) scholars, historians, and playwrights, has left an indelible mark. Its influence permeates the vocabulary of English and countless other European languages, a testament to its enduring legacy. Since the [Renaissance](/Renaissance), it has held a prominent, almost sacrosanct, position in Western educational curricula. Furthermore, the [Latinized](/Latinisation_of_names) forms of Ancient Greek roots are indispensable in the nomenclature of scientific disciplines, forming the bedrock of terminology across various fields. [Koine Greek](/Koine_Greek), once the unifying [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) of the Eastern Roman Empire, continues its existence as a sacred liturgical language within some [Eastern Orthodox churches](/Eastern_Orthodox_churches). This lineage eventually evolved through [Medieval Greek](/Medieval_Greek) into the [Modern Greek](/Modern_Greek) we recognize today.

Latin, for its part, served as the indispensable [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) of the nascent [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire) and subsequently its Western counterpart. Even as the Western Roman Empire crumbled, Latin's vitality endured. It thrived in the vastly altered social and economic landscape of the [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages), notably becoming the official language of the [Roman Catholic Church](/Roman_Catholic_Church).

Across Western and Central Europe, and extending into portions of North Africa, Latin maintained its elevated status as the primary medium of discourse for the educated elite throughout the Middle Ages and into the [Early modern period](/Early_modern_period). Even in the 21st century, Latin continues to be taught, predominantly in prestigious private institutions within the United States.&#91;2&#93;

The dominance of Latin in scientific discourse persisted until the 18th century. Its influence lingered even longer in the formal descriptions within [zoology](/Zoology) and [botany], surviving well into the latter half of the 20th century. The modern system of international [binomial nomenclature](/Binomial_nomenclature), a cornerstone of biological classification, adheres to this tradition, with taxonomists assigning Latin or Latinized names to each [species](/Species).

The spoken, non-formal variants of Latin, collectively known as [Vulgar Latin](/Vulgar_Latin), which circulated from the Late Roman Republic onwards, are the direct ancestors of the [Neo-Latin languages](/Neo-Latin_languages), a diverse family that includes [Spanish](/Spanish_language), [Portuguese](/Portuguese_language), [French](/French_language), [Italian](/Italian_language), [Romanian](/Romanian_language), and [Catalan](/Catalan_language), among others.

### Classical Languages in Asia

When considering languages of global cultural significance, the esteemed linguist [Edward Sapir](/Edward_Sapir), in his seminal 1921 work [Language](/Language:_An_Introduction_to_the_Study_of_Speech), expanded this esteemed list to encompass [classical Chinese](/Classical_Chinese), [Sanskrit](/Classical_Sanskrit), and [Arabic](/Classical_Arabic).

Sapir eloquently articulated this perspective: "When we realize that an educated [Japanese](/Japanese_people) can hardly frame a single literary sentence without the use of Chinese resources, that to this day [Siamese](/Thai_language) and [Burmese](/Burmese_language) and [Cambodgian](/Khmer_language) bear the unmistakable imprint of the Sanskrit and [Pali](/Pali_language) that came in with Hindu Buddhism centuries ago, or that whether we argue for or against the teaching of Latin and Greek [in schools,] our argument is sure to be studded with words that have come to us from [Rome](/Rome) and [Athens](/Athens), we get some indication of what early Chinese culture and [Buddhism](/Buddhism), and classical [Mediterranean civilization](/Mediterranean_civilization) have meant in the world's history. There are just five languages that have had an overwhelming significance as carriers of culture. They are classical Chinese, Sanskrit, Arabic, Greek, and Latin. In comparison with these, even such culturally important languages as [Hebrew](/Hebrew_language) and [French](/French_language) sink into a secondary position." &#91;3&#93;

Within this framework, a classical language is defined by its extensive and enduring influence over a prolonged temporal span, even after its vernacular form has faded into disuse. The adoption of roots from one language by another to forge new terminology, as is evident in the way many [European languages](/European_languages) draw upon Greek and Latin [roots](/Root_(linguistics)) to create words like "telephone," serves as a powerful indicator that the source language holds classical status.&#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93;

In contrast, contemporary languages that wield considerable global influence are categorized as [world languages](/World_language).

