The following languages are widely recognized as having passed through a distinct "classical" stage. This stage is temporally defined and deemed "classical" when it is retrospectively perceived as a period of literary brilliance, a veritable "golden age."&#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93; For instance, [Classical Greek](/Ancient_Greek) refers specifically to the language of [Athens](/Classical_Athens) during the 5th and 4th centuries BC, representing a specific subset within the broader spectrum of the [Greek language](/Greek_language). Typically, a "classical" period follows an "archaic" phase and is characterized by a flourishing of literature. Examples include [Classical Latin](/Classical_Latin) succeeding [Old Latin](/Old_Latin), [Classical Sumerian](/Sumerian_language) following Archaic Sumerian, [Tamil](/Tamil_language) recognized for its continuous literary tradition, Classical Sanskrit emerging after [Vedic Sanskrit](/Vedic_Sanskrit), and [Classical Persian](/Persian_language) succeeding [Old Persian](/Old_Persian). The precise classification can sometimes be a matter of terminology; for instance, [Old Chinese](/Old_Chinese) is often considered inclusive of, rather than preceding, [Classical Chinese](/Classical_Chinese). In certain cases, such as with [Persian](/Persian_language), the "classical" stage corresponds to the earliest period for which literary evidence exists.&#91;4&#93;

#### Antiquity

*   [Classical Sumerian](/Sumerian_language): The literary language of [Sumer](/Sumer), flourishing approximately from the 26th to the 23rd centuries BC. [Sumerograms](/Sumerogram) persisted in [Cuneiform](/Cuneiform) script even for texts not in Sumerian until the script's eventual disuse around the 1st century AD.
*   [Middle Egyptian](/Egyptian_language): The principal literary language of [Ancient Egypt](/Ancient_Egypt), employed from roughly the 20th century BC to the 4th century AD.
*   [Old Babylonian](/Akkadian_language): Representing the Akkadian language from approximately the 20th to the 16th centuries BC, it served as the imitated standard for subsequent literary compositions.
*   [Middle Assyrian](/Akkadian_language): The Akkadian language during the period of approximately the 16th to the 13th centuries BC.
*   [Old Avestan](/Avestan): The language utilized in the sacred texts of the [Avesta](/Avesta), dating from the 15th to the 5th centuries BC.
*   [Vedic Sanskrit](/Vedic_Sanskrit): The form of Sanskrit that predates its Classical standardization, found in Vedic texts from approximately the 15th to the 5th centuries BC.
*   [Classical Hebrew](/Biblical_Hebrew): The language of the [Tanakh](/Hebrew_Bible), particularly evident in the [prophetic books](/Nevi%27im) composed around the 7th and 6th centuries BC.
*   [Old Persian](/Old_Persian): The official court language of the [Achaemenid Empire](/Achaemenid_Empire), used from the 6th to the 4th centuries BC.
*   [Classical Chinese](/Classical_Chinese): Based on the literary language known as [Yayan](/Yayan_(language)), which was spoken in the capital city of [Luoyang](/Luoyang) during the [Eastern Zhou Dynasty](/Eastern_Zhou), from approximately the 5th century BC onwards.
*   [Classical Greek](/Ancient_Greek): Specifically, the [Attic dialect](/Attic_Greek) prevalent in the 5th century BC.
*   [Classical Sanskrit](/Sanskrit): Systematized by [Pāṇini's](/P%C4%81%E1%B9%87ini) renowned grammatical work, the [Ashtadhyayi](/A%E1%B9%A3%E1%B9%AD%C4%81dhy%C4%AB), dating back to the 4th century BC.&#91;5&#93;&#91;6&#93;
*   [Classical Tamil](/Old_Tamil): Characterized by the [Sangam literature](/Sangam_literature), spanning from approximately the 3rd century BC to the 3rd century AD, and codified by the grammatical treatise [Tolkāppiyam](/Tolk%C4%81ppiyam).&#91;7&#93;
*   [Classical Pali](/Pali): The language of the Buddhist canon, in use from the 2nd century BC.
*   [Maharashtri Prakrit](/Maharashtri_Prakrit): A prominent [Prakrit](/Prakrit) language that served as the official tongue of the Satavahana dynasty around the 2nd century BC.
*   [Classical Latin](/Classical_Latin): The esteemed literary language of the 1st century BC.
*   [Classical Mandaic](/Mandaic_language): The literary [Aramaic](/Aramaic) used within the Mandaean faith ([Mandaeism](/Mandaeism)), originating in the 1st century AD.
*   [Classical Syriac](/Syriac_language): The literary [Aramaic](/Aramaic) associated with [Syriac Christianity](/Syriac_Christianity), flourishing from the 3rd to the 5th centuries AD.
*   [Middle Persian](/Middle_Persian): The court language of the [Sassanid Empire](/Sasanian_Empire), used from the 3rd to the 7th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Coptic](/Coptic_language): The language of Egypt and the [Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria](/Coptic_Orthodox_Church), used from the 3rd to the 13th centuries AD, and still maintained as a liturgical language.

#### Middle Ages

*   [Geʽez](/Ge%CA%BDez): The liturgical language of the [Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church](/Ethiopian_Orthodox_Tewahedo_Church). The [Garima Gospels](/Garima_Gospels) are attributed by scholars to a period between the 5th and 10th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Armenian](/Classical_Armenian): The earliest attested form of the [Armenian language](/Armenian_language), dating from the 5th century AD, and serving as the literary language until the 18th century.
*   [Classical Arabic](/Classical_Arabic): Based on the language of the [Qur'an](/Quran), this form dates from the 7th century AD to the present and remains the liturgical language of [Islam](/Islam).
*   [Classical Kannada](/Kannada): Served as the court language of the [Rashtrakuta empire](/Rashtrakuta_dynasty). The earliest extant literary work is the [Kavirājamārga](/Kavirajamarga), dating from AD 850.&#91;8&#93;
*   [Old Saxon](/Old_Saxon): The language used in Saxon Christian literature, from the 9th to the 12th centuries AD.
*   [Old English](/Old_English): The language of epic works like [Beowulf](/Beowulf) and historical records such as the [Anglo-Saxon Chronicle](/Anglo-Saxon_Chronicle). While exhibiting numerous dialectal variations in writing, it achieved a degree of standardization in the [West Saxon](/West_Saxon_dialect) form.
*   [Old French](/Old_French): The language of the [chivalric romance](/Chivalric_romance) genre, prevalent from the 8th to the 14th centuries AD.
*   [Old Georgian](/Old_Georgian): The language of Georgia, attested from the 5th to the 11th centuries AD.
*   [Old East Slavic](/Old_East_Slavic): The language spoken in [Kievan Rus'](/Kievan_Rus%27), from the 9th to the 13th centuries AD.
*   [New Persian](/New_Persian): The language of classical [Persian literature](/Persian_literature), spanning from the 9th century AD to the present.
*   [Old Nubian](/Old_Nubian): The language used in [Nubia](/Nubia), from the 9th or 10th to the 15th centuries AD.
*   [Old Assamese](/Assamese_language): The earliest form of the [Assamese language](/Assamese_language), documented between the 7th and 12th centuries CE, emerging during the era of the [Kamarupa kingdom](/Kamarupa_kingdom).&#91;9&#93;&#91;10&#93;&#91;11&#93;&#91;12&#93;
*   [Old Bengali](/Old_Bengali): The earliest manifestations of the [Bengali Language](/Bengali_Language), originating during the [Kingdom of Gauda](/Kingdom_of_Gauda), from the 7th to the 12th centuries AD.&#91;13&#93;
*   [Old Javanese](/Old_Javanese): The language of [Javanese literature](/Javanese_literature), primarily utilized during the [Hindu-Buddhist](/Javanese_people) Javanese kingdoms from the 10th to the 15th centuries AD.&#91;14&#93;&#91;15&#93;
*   [Old Church Slavonic](/Old_Church_Slavonic): The language of the [First Bulgarian Empire](/First_Bulgarian_Empire) during its Golden Age, with the earliest manuscript, the [Freising manuscripts](/Freising_manuscripts), dating to the 10th century AD.
*   [Classical Tibetan](/Classical_Tibetan): The religious and literary language of Tibet, in use from the 10th century AD to the present.
*   [Classical Japanese](/Classical_Japanese): The language of literature during the [Heian period](/Heian_period), from the 10th to the 12th centuries AD.
*   [Middle Korean](/Middle_Korean): The language spoken during the Goryeo and [Joseon](/Joseon) dynasties, from the 10th to the 16th centuries AD.
*   [Old Occitan](/Old_Occitan): The language favored by the [troubadours](/Troubadour), from the 11th to the 14th centuries AD.
*   [Middle High German](/Middle_High_German): The language of [Medieval German literature](/Middle_High_German_literature), from the 11th to the 14th centuries AD.
*   [Old Serbian](/Old_Church_Slavonic): The language of [Serbia](/Serbia) prior to its subjugation by the [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire), from the 11th to the 14th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Telugu](/Telugu_language): The earliest available literary work is the Telugu Mahabharata, dated AD 1067.
*   [Classical Malayalam](/Malayalam): The earliest extant prose work is the Ramacharitam, dating to the 12th century AD.&#91;16&#93;
*   [Classical Odia](/Odia_language): The language of [Odia literature](/Odia_literature). The earliest attested history of the [Old Odia](/Old_Odia) language dates back to the Ganga dynasty, from the 7th to 12th centuries CE.&#91;17&#93;
*   [Old Norse](/Old_Norse): The language of the [Viking Age](/Viking_Age), from the 12th century AD.
*   [Middle Bulgarian](/Middle_Bulgarian): The language of the [Second Bulgarian Empire](/Second_Bulgarian_Empire), from the 12th to the 15th centuries AD.
*   [Middle Low German](/Middle_Low_German): The language of the [Hanseatic League](/Hanseatic_League), from the 12th to the 17th centuries AD.
*   [Old Uyghur](/Old_Uyghur): A Turkic language spoken in [Qocho](/Qocho) from the 9th to 14th centuries AD, and also in Gansu.
*   [Classical Icelandic](/Sagas_of_Icelanders): The language of the [Icelandic sagas](/Sagas_of_Icelanders), from the 13th century AD.
*   [Classical Catalan](/Old_Catalan): The literary language within the [Crown of Aragon](/Crown_of_Aragon), from the 13th to the 14th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Manding](/Mandinka_language): The language of the [Mali Empire](/Mali_Empire), from the 13th to the 16th centuries AD.
*   [Old Ruthenian](/Ruthenian_language): One of the languages used in the [Grand Duchy of Lithuania](/Grand_Duchy_of_Lithuania), from the 13th to the 16th centuries AD.
*   [Old Anatolian Turkish](/Old_Anatolian_Turkish): Spoken from the 11th to the 15th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Ge'ez](/Ge%CA%BDez): The language of the [Golden Age of Ge'ez literature](/Ethiopian_literature), from the 13th to the 16th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Irish or Classical Gaelic](/Early_Modern_Irish): The language of Scottish and Irish Gaelic literature from the 13th to the 18th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Wolof](/Wolof_language): The language of the [Wolof Empire](/Jolof_Empire), from the 13th to the 19th centuries AD.
*   [Middle English](/Middle_English): The language of Geoffrey Chaucer's [The Canterbury Tales](/The_Canterbury_Tales), used from the 14th to the 15th centuries AD. While diverse in its written forms, it saw partial standardization based on London speech.
*   [Middle French](/Middle_French): The language of the [French Renaissance](/French_Renaissance), from the 14th to the 17th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Hungarian](/History_of_the_Hungarian_language): The language of [Hungarian literature](/Hungarian_literature) during the 14th and 15th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Songhai](/Songhay_languages): The [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) of the [Songhai Empire](/Songhai_Empire), from the 14th to the 16th centuries AD.
*   [Early New High German](/Early_New_High_German): The language of the [Holy Roman Empire](/Holy_Roman_Empire), the [German Renaissance](/German_Renaissance), and the [Protestant Reformation](/Reformation), used from the 14th to the 17th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Malay](/History_of_the_Malay_language): The language of [Maritime Southeast Asia](/Maritime_Southeast_Asia), from the 14th to the 18th centuries AD.
*   [Chagatai](/Chagatai_language): A classical Turkic language of Central Asia and the Volga region, used from the 14th to the early 20th centuries AD.
*   [Angkorian Old Khmer](/Old_Khmer): The language of the [Khmer Empire](/Khmer_Empire), dating from the 14th century AD.
*   [Rekhta](/Rekhta): A poetic language originating in [Delhi](/Delhi) and the northern/central Indian subcontinent, used from the 13th to 18th centuries AD, which later standardized into [Urdu](/Urdu) in the 19th century.

#### Amerindian Languages

*   [Classical Maya](/Classic_Maya_language): The language of the mature [Maya civilization](/Maya_civilization), from the 3rd to the 9th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Nahuatl](/Classical_Nahuatl): The [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) of central Mexico in the 16th century AD.
*   [Classical Quechua](/Classical_Quechua): The [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) of the [Inca Empire](/Inca_Empire) in the 16th century AD.
*   [Classical Kʼicheʼ](/Classical_K%CA%BCiche%CA%BC): A [Mayan language](/Mayan_languages) spoken in 16th-century [Guatemala](/Guatemala).
*   [Classical Tupi](/Tupi_language): The language of [Brazil](/Brazil) from the 16th to 18th centuries AD.

#### Early Modern Period

*   [Awadhi](/Awadhi_language): One of the two primary literary traditions of Northern India during the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire), leading to its adoption by poets from the 14th to 18th centuries AD.
*   [Braj Bhasha](/Braj_literature): The other major literary tradition in early modern Northern India, extensively used by poets from the 15th to 19th centuries AD.
*   [Renaissance Italian](/Italian_language): The language of the [Italian Renaissance](/Italian_Renaissance), from the 15th to 16th centuries AD.
*   [Late Old Portuguese](/History_of_Portuguese): The language of the [Portuguese Golden Age](/History_of_Portugal_(1415%E2%80%931578)), from the 15th to 16th centuries AD.
*   [Early Modern Spanish](/Early_Modern_Spanish): The language of the [Spanish Golden Age](/Spanish_Golden_Age), from the 15th to 17th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Azeri](/Azerbaijani_literature): The [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) of the Caucasus Mountain region and the language of Azeri literature, from the 15th to 18th centuries AD.
*   [Old Lithuanian](/Lithuanian_language): The other significant language of the [Grand Duchy of Lithuania](/Grand_Duchy_of_Lithuania), used from the 16th to 17th centuries AD.
*   [Early Modern English](/Early_Modern_English): The language of seminal works like the [King James Bible](/King_James_Version), the [Book of Common Prayer](/Book_of_Common_Prayer), and the plays of [William Shakespeare](/William_Shakespeare), from the 16th to 17th centuries AD.
*   [Middle Polish](/Middle_Polish): The language of the [Polish Golden Age](/Polish_Golden_Age), from the 16th to 18th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Ottoman Turkish](/Ottoman_Turkish): The language of poetry and administration within the [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire), from the 16th to 19th centuries AD.
*   [Manchu language](/Manchu_language): The language of the Manchus, who ruled China, used from the 16th to the 20th centuries AD.
*   [Early Modern Dutch](/History_of_the_Dutch_language): The language of the [Dutch Golden Age](/Dutch_Golden_Age), particularly in the 17th century AD.
*   [Early Modern French](/History_of_French): The language of [France](/France) under the reigns of [Louis XIV](/Louis_XIV) through [Napoleon](/Napoleon), from the 17th to 18th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Ladino](/Judaeo-Spanish): The language of [Sephardic Jewish literature](/Sephardic_Jews), used from the 17th to 19th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Russian](/History_of_the_Russian_language): The language of the [Russian Empire](/Russian_Empire), from the 18th to 19th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Mongolian language](/Classical_Mongolian_language): The language of Mongolian literature and translations of Tibetan Buddhist religious texts, used from 1700 to 1900 AD.
*   [Sadhu Bhasha](/Sadhu_bhasha): The standardized Bengali language used in literature from the 1820s to the 1940s AD.
*   [Classical Yiddish](/Yiddish): The language that experienced a renaissance, particularly in the 19th and 20th centuries AD.
*   [Classical Newar](/Classical_Newar): Served as a [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) in the India-Tibet trade.

